[src:federal-league/1913-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1913 throughout the world.
[src:federal-league/1914-baltimore-terrapins-season] The 1914 Baltimore Terrapins season was a season in American baseball.
[src:federal-league/1914-baltimore-terrapins-season] They finished in third place in the Federal League, 4½ games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:federal-league/1914-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The **1914 Brooklyn Tip-Tops season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:federal-league/1914-brooklyn-tip-tops-season] The Tip-Tops finished in 5th place in the Federal League, 11½ games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:federal-league/1914-buffalo-buffeds-season] The **1914 Buffalo Buffeds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:federal-league/1914-buffalo-buffeds-season] The Buffeds finished 80–71, good for 4th place in the Federal League, 7 games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:federal-league/1914-chicago-federals-season] The **1914 Chicago Federals season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:federal-league/1914-chicago-federals-season] Chicago finished 87–67, good for 2nd place in the Federal League, just 1½ games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:federal-league/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1914 Indianapolis Hoosiers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:federal-league/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The Hoosiers won the inaugural Federal League championship, finishing 88–65, 1½ games ahead of the Chicago Federals.
[src:federal-league/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The offensive star of the team was outfielder Benny Kauff, who led the league in batting average (.370), runs scored (120), and stolen bases (75).
[src:federal-league/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Future Hall of Famers Edd Roush and Bill McKechnie also saw significant playing time, and Indianapolis scored a league-high 762 runs.
[src:federal-league/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Their rotation ace, Cy Falkenberg, went 25–16 with a 2.22 earned run average; he topped the circuit with 236 strikeouts.
[src:federal-league/1914-kansas-city-packers-season] The **1914 Kansas City Packers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:federal-league/1914-kansas-city-packers-season] The Packers finished in 6th place in the Federal League, 20 games behind the Indianapolis Hoosiers.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League came together in early 1913 through the work of John T.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Powers, and immediately challenged the operations of organized baseball as a minor league playing outside of the National Agreement.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Gilmore succeeded Powers as league president, the league declared itself to be a major league.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Playing in what detractors called the "outlaw" league allowed players to avoid the restrictions of the organized leagues' reserve clause.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The competition of another, better paying league caused players' salaries to skyrocket, demonstrating the bargaining potential of free agency for the first time since the war between the AL and NL.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Interference by the National and American Leagues in their operations caused the Federal League to fold after the 1915 season.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] This resulted in a landmark federal lawsuit, *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Supreme Court ultimately ruled that the Sherman Antitrust Act did not apply to Major League Baseball.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League left its mark on baseball history in the field now known as Wrigley Field, which was originally built for the Chicago Whales Federal League team.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The league itself and many sports writers considered it a major league during its existence; organized baseball recognized its major league status in 1968.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Not including the Negro Major Leagues, it would be the last independent major league outside the established structure of professional baseball to make it to the playing field, and would be the last serious attempt to create a third major league until the abortive Continental League of 1960.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Powers formed an independent professional league known as the **Columbian League**.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] However, the withdrawal of one of the organization's primary investors caused the league to fail before ever playing a game.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Undaunted, Powers tried again the following year, creating a new league with teams in Chicago, Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Indianapolis, St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] He named the organization the Federal League, and served as its first president.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Because it did not abide by the National Agreement on player payment in place in organized baseball, the Federal League was called an "outlaw league" by its competitors.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League's outlaw status allowed it to recruit players from established clubs, and it attracted many current and former players from the major as well as minor leagues.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In 1913, the Federal League played as an independent six-team minor league.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In its first season Powers initially served as president, but he was soon replaced by James A.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Gilmore, under whose leadership the league declared itself a major league for the 1914 season.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Other financiers of the League included oil baron Harry F.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Sinclair, ice magnate Phil Ball, and George S.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] As a major circuit, the Federal League consisted of eight teams each season.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Four of the teams were placed in cities with existing major league baseball teams (Chicago, St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The other four teams were placed in areas without a current major league club (Baltimore, Buffalo, Indianapolis and Kansas City).
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In the first year, 1914, some of the teams had official nicknames and some did not, but either way, sportswriters were inclined to invent their own nicknames: "ChiFeds," "BrookFeds," etc.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In order for the Federal League to succeed, it needed Big League players.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Walter Johnson signed a three-year contract with the Chicago team, but the Senators' Clark Griffith went personally to Johnson's home in Kansas and made a successful counter-offer.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Major League players that jumped to the Federal League included Bill McKechnie, Claude Hendrix, Jack Quinn, Russell Ford, Tom Seaton, Doc Crandall, Al Bridwell, and Hal Chase.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League also recruited Big League names to manage the new teams.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Joe Tinker managed the Chicago team, Mordecai Brown managed the St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis team and Bill Bradley managed the Brooklyn team.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In 1914, the Colonial League began to operate as a Class C level league based in Southern New England.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In April, Alexander Bannwart drew notice by acquiring Big Jeff Pfeffer to manage the team in Pawtucket, Rhode Island, and by May, it was suspected that Bannwart was working as an agent of the Federal League, which Bannwart denied.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Upon these news reports, some of the founding members of the Colonial League resigned, fearing banishment by the National Baseball Commission.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] At the April 1915 league meeting, Coppen was re-elected as president and Bannwart was elected secretary.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Ward, the treasurer of the Brooklyn Tip-Tops of the Federal League and George S.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Ward's son, was elected as the league's treasurer.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Colonial League reorganized itself as a farm system for the Federal League and voluntarily withdrew itself from organized baseball.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League had close pennant races both years.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In 1914, Indianapolis beat out Chicago by 1½ games.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] 1915 witnessed the tightest pennant race in Major League history, as three teams (Chicago, St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis and Pittsburgh) fought into the last weekend of the season.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] On the season's final day, Sunday, October 3, Chicago split a doubleheader with Pittsburgh, winning the darkness-shortened seven-inning nightcap, 3-0; this combined with St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis' 6-2 win over Kansas City, knocked Pittsburgh back to third (albeit just a half-game behind), with Chicago and St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] But since the Whales (86-66) played two fewer games than the St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis Terriers (87-67), they were awarded the pennant based on their slightly better winning percentage (.566 to .565).
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Pittsburgh, with one game unplayed, ended up at 86-67 (.562).
[src:federal-league/federal-league] During the 1914–15 offseason, Federal League owners brought an antitrust lawsuit against the American and National Leagues.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The lawsuit ended up in the court of Federal Judge (and future Commissioner of Baseball) Kenesaw Mountain Landis, who allowed the case to languish while he urged both sides to negotiate.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Swift action might have made a difference, but without the lawsuit going forward, the Federals found themselves in deepening financial straits.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] After the 1915 season, the owners of the American and National Leagues bought out half of the owners (Pittsburgh, Newark, Buffalo, and Brooklyn) of the Federal League teams.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Two Federal League owners were allowed to buy struggling franchises in the established leagues: Phil Ball, owner of the St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis Terriers, was allowed to buy the St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis Browns of the AL, and Charles Weeghman, owner of the Chicago Whales, bought the Chicago Cubs.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Both owners merged their teams into the established ones.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Kansas City franchise had been declared bankrupt and taken over by the league office after the close of the regular season, and the Baltimore owners rejected the offer made to them.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] They had sought to buy and move an existing franchise to their city, but were rebuffed, and sued unsuccessfully.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] One of baseball's most famous ballparks was originally built for a Federal League team: Wrigley Field, the home of the Chicago Cubs, began its long life as Weeghman Park, the home of the Chicago Whales.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Marc Okkonen, in his book on the Federal League, referred to Wrigley as a "silent monument" to the failed Federal League experiment.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Otherwise, few visible remnants were left by the short-lived Federal League.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Baltimore entry sold their facility to the Baltimore Orioles of the International League, who renamed it Oriole Park and played there for nearly 30 years before it was destroyed by fire.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Newark ballpark was also used for minor league ball for a short time.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Washington Park III in Brooklyn, completed after the 1915 season was underway, resembled Chicago's Weeghman Park.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] It was used for various sports until the end of 1917 and then for storage until Brooklyn Edison Electric bought the property in 1925 and shortly thereafter tore it down.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The other Federal League ballparks were demolished quickly, including the home of the Pittsburgh Rebels, Exposition Park, which had been the home of the Pittsburgh Pirates of the National League until they moved into Forbes Field in 1909.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The other "silent monument" to the Federal League is a famous legal decision.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In 1922, the Supreme Court ruled in *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Though significantly weakened in the 1970s, this exemption remains intact 104 years later; however, it has been eroded by subsequent court rulings and legislation regarding issues specific to Major League Baseball.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Of the locations of teams in the Federal League, five currently have major league teams.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Those are Baltimore, Chicago, Kansas City, Pittsburgh and St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Brooklyn has a minor league team, the Brooklyn Cyclones.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Newark had a team, the Bears, in the independent Can-Am League, which folded after the 2012 season.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] There is at least one achievement of note that happened in Federal League play.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis Terriers, won his milestone 300th game on September 11, 1915, at St.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Louis' Handlan's Park, becoming the first 300-game winning left-hander in the history of major league baseball and one of only six as of 2018.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] However, that milestone was not acknowledged by Major League Baseball until 1968.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League was the last serious attempt at creating a "third major league" outside the established structure of professional baseball in the U.S.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] There was one further attempt at creating a third league – the Continental League in 1959 – but its founders had hoped to find their place within the purview of organized baseball.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Continental League disbanded in 1960 without ever playing a game, making the Federal League the last such league to ever take to the field.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] The Federal League features prominently in Ring Lardner's sports humor book *You Know Me Al* (1916), in which the protagonist pitches for the Chicago White Sox and repeatedly threatens to jump to the Federal League whenever he feels underappreciated or underpaid.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Players in the Baseball Hall of Fame who played in the Federal League are listed below.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Each of these players was elected via the Veterans Committee.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] In addition, Cy Young managed the 1913 Cleveland Green Sox.
[src:federal-league/federal-league] Per final regular season standings, as there was no postseason.
